.ie \n(.g .ds Aq \(aq
.el .ds Aq '
.TH task 1  "task " 
.SH NAME
task \- Manage and execute operational tasks (skills)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBtask\fR [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] <\fIsubcommands\fR>
.SH DESCRIPTION
Manage and execute operational tasks (skills).
.PP
Tasks are markdown\-defined skills that the agent executes. System tasks ship in /usr/share/regin/skills/. User tasks go in ~/.config/regin/skills/. User tasks override system tasks with the same name.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
task\-list(1)
List all available tasks
.TP
task\-show(1)
Show details of a task: its prompt and supporting files
.TP
task\-exec(1)
Execute a task, optionally scheduling it for repeated execution
.TP
task\-unschedule(1)
Remove a recurring schedule for a task
.TP
task\-schedules(1)
List all active task schedules
.TP
task\-create(1)
Create a new task (skill) in the user skills dir
.TP
task\-help(1)
Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)
.SH EXTRA
SKILL FORMAT:
  Each skill is a directory containing skill.md (the prompt) and
  optional supporting files. The first line of skill.md is the
  description shown in \*(Aqtask list\*(Aq.
